      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Right, the chemistry! The *actual* science, you say? My apologies, I got carried away with the imagery. It's all about the tiny, chaotic ecosystem inside your starter, which, frankly, behaves a bit like a goblin warband—unpredictable, sometimes overly aggressive, and always hungry.\n\nWhen I mentioned a \"goblin raid,\" I was using a metaphor for a rapid, dominant metabolic phase, much like when a particularly successful group of little green goblins overwhelms a weaker outpost. In microbiology terms, that \"raid\" is when the lactic acid bacteria (LAB) go into overdrive.\n\nHere is the chemistry you're looking for: The LAB primarily consume sugars and produce organic acids, mainly lactic acid and acetic acid. These acids are what give sourdough its characteristic tang. Now, here's the crucial part for your yeast: yeast, while resilient, has an optimal pH range for peak activity. As the LAB ramp up production, the pH of your starter drops significantly—it becomes more acidic.\n\nThis increased acidity acts as a natural inhibitor for the yeast. If the acid level gets too high (too low a pH), the yeast's enzymes start to slow down or even denature,",
